generalfeedback.text:
Worked solution

Given the rational expression \( \displaystyle {@frac_1@}-{@frac_2@}+{@frac_3@}\).

a. Find the least common multiple of the denominators of the expression above.

\(lcm= \displaystyle {@common_den@} \)

b. Perform the indicated operations and simplify your result.

Let's recall the common denominator, which is \( \displaystyle {@common_den@}\)

  • To write \(\displaystyle {@frac_1@}\) as a fraction with a common denominator, we multiply it by \( \displaystyle \frac{@common_den/den_first_frac@}{@common_den/den_first_frac@} \):
    \(\displaystyle {@frac_1@} =\displaystyle \frac{@num_first_frac*(common_den/den_first_frac)@}{@common_den@} \)
  • To write \(\displaystyle {@-frac_2@}\) as a fraction with a common denominator, we multiply it by \( \displaystyle \frac{@common_den/den_second_frac@}{@common_den/den_second_frac@} \):
    \( \displaystyle {@-frac_2@} = \displaystyle - \frac{@num_second_frac*(common_den/den_second_frac)@}{@common_den@} \)
  • To write \(\displaystyle {@frac_3@}\) as a fraction with a common denominator, we multiply it by \( \displaystyle \frac{@common_den/den_third_frac@}{@common_den/den_third_frac@} \):
    \( \displaystyle {@frac_3@} = \displaystyle \frac{@num_third_frac*(common_den/den_third_frac)@}{@common_den@} \)

    • Combining all the three fractions over a common denominator, we obtain

    \(\displaystyle \frac{@num_first_frac*(common_den/den_first_frac)@}{@common_den@} - \frac{@num_second_frac*(common_den/den_second_frac)@}{@common_den@} + \frac{@num_third_frac*(common_den/den_third_frac)@}{@common_den@} = \displaystyle {@ta_1@}\)

    Therefore, \( \displaystyle {@frac_1@}-{@frac_2@}+{@frac_3@}= \displaystyle {@ta_1@}\).
